=== 2.2 Dot Product

The *dot product* (also called inner product) of two vectors stem:[u, v \in \mathbb{R}^n] is a scalar:

stem:[u \cdot v = \sum_{i=1}^{n} u_i v_i = u_1 v_1 + u_2 v_2 + \ldots + u_n v_n]

Two key properties:

- *Geometric interpretation:* stem:[u \cdot v = \|u\| \|v\| \cos\theta], where stem:[\theta] is the angle between them.
  When stem:[u \cdot v = 0], the vectors are orthogonal (perpendicular).
- *Similarity measure:* if stem:[u] and stem:[v] are unit vectors, stem:[u \cdot v \in [-1, 1\]] is their cosine similarity.
  Attention scores in GPT are dot products between query and key vectors (Chapter 6).

==== Scheme Implementation

[source,scheme]
----
(define (dot-product u v)
  (apply + (map * u v)))
----

==== Example

Let stem:[u = [3, 4, 0\]] and stem:[v = [1, -2, 5\]]:

stem:[u \cdot v = (3)(1) + (4)(-2) + (0)(5) = 3 - 8 + 0 = -5]

Cosine similarity requires unit vectors.
stem:[\|u\| = \sqrt{9+16+0} = 5], so stem:[\hat{u} = [0.6, 0.8, 0\]].
stem:[\|v\| = \sqrt{1+4+25} = \sqrt{30}], so stem:[\hat{v} = [0.183, -0.365, 0.913\]].

stem:[\hat{u} \cdot \hat{v} = (0.6)(0.183) + (0.8)(-0.365) + 0 = 0.110 - 0.292 = -0.182]

The vectors point in moderately opposite directions.

Running in Scheme:

[source,scheme]
----
(display (dot-product '(3 4 0) '(1 -2 5)))   ; => -5
(display (dot-product '(1 0) '(0 1)))          ; => 0  (orthogonal)
(display (dot-product '(1 0) '(1 0)))          ; => 1  (identical unit vectors)
----

